The documentary describes the history of the Jews of Spain, known as the Sephardic Jews, or Sephardim. Following the expulsion of Jews from Judea by the Romans ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â‚¬Å“ known as the Diaspora, Jews settled all around the known world of the time. The two principle groups were the Northern European Jews, called the Ashkenazi, which make up the Jews best known today in Western Culture. They settled in Poland, Russia, Eastern Europe, Germany and so forth. Largely destroyed by the Pogroms and the Holocaust, they are also the majority of the Jews that came to settle in America and in modern Israel.

The Sephardic (also called Oriental) Jews settled mostly in what came to be the Muslim lands, especially in the Moorish areas of North Africa. The Muslim Moors led the expansion of Islam into Spain and France, holding these lands for about 7 centuries until their eventual expulsion under the Catholic Spanish Reconquista. This was a golden age for Sephardic Jewry, resulting in famous writings, science, philosophy and great teachers. This was also a principal era for the development of Jewish Mysticism, especially the writings known as the Zohar and the Kabbalah. The great Rabbi Maimonides (known as the Rambam, and from whom I chose my internet name) lived in Spain during this period. Following the expulsion of the Muslims, many of the Jews who remained suddenly became oppressed and maltreated, shoved largely into cramped and pitiful areas, giving us our modern word Ghetto. In 1492, they were formally expelled from Spain all together, except for some ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‹Å“conversosÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢ who pretended to have converted to Catholicism. These Jews were called Marranos or Crypto-Jews, and often spoke the Jewish/Spanish hybrid language called Ladino. The last remnants today live in Portugal.

